    <section id="about" class="content-section mb-5">
        <h2 class="section-title">What is Sudoku?</h2>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-8">
                <p class="lead">
                    Sudoku is a logic-based number-placement puzzle that has captivated millions worldwide. 
                    The objective is to fill a 9×9 grid with digits so that each column, each row, and each 
                    of the nine 3×3 subgrids contains all of the digits from 1 to 9.
                </p>
                <p>
                    What makes Sudoku fascinating is that it requires no mathematical calculations—only logic, 
                    pattern recognition, and patience. Each puzzle has a unique solution that can be reached 
                    through logical deduction alone.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h5 class="fw-bold">Quick Facts</h5>
                    <ul class="list-unstyled">
                        <li>📊 Grid: 9×9 (81 cells)</li>
                        <li>🔢 Numbers: 1-9</li>
                        <li>🎯 Regions: 9 rows, 9 columns, 9 boxes</li>
                        <li>🧩 Solution: Always unique</li>
                        <li>🧠 Skills: Logic & pattern recognition</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section mb-5">
        <h2 class="section-title">History of Sudoku</h2>
        <div class="timeline">
            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-marker">1783</div>
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <h5>Latin Squares</h5>
                    <p>
                        Swiss mathematician <strong>Leonhard Euler</strong> created "Latin Squares," 
                        a mathematical concept that would later inspire Sudoku. These were n×n grids 
                        filled with n different symbols, ensuring each symbol appeared once per row and column.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-marker">1979</div>
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <h5>Modern Sudoku is Born</h5>
                    <p>
                        American architect <strong>Howard Garns</strong> created the first modern Sudoku 
                        puzzle, originally called <em>"Number Place"</em>. It was published in Dell Magazines' 
                        puzzle books. Garns added the crucial 3×3 regional constraint to Euler's concept.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-marker">1984</div>
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <h5>Arrives in Japan</h5>
                    <p>
                        The puzzle was introduced to Japan by puzzle publisher <strong>Nikoli</strong>, 
                        who named it <strong>"Sūji wa dokushin ni kagiru"</strong> (数字は独身に限る), 
                        meaning "the digits must be single" or "the digits are limited to one occurrence." 
                        This was later shortened to <strong>"Sudoku"</strong> (数独), combining 
                        <em>sū</em> (number) and <em>doku</em> (single).
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-marker">2004</div>
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <h5>Global Phenomenon</h5>
                    <p>
                        <strong>Wayne Gould</strong>, a retired Hong Kong judge, discovered Sudoku during 
                        a trip to Japan. He spent six years developing a computer program to generate puzzles 
                        and convinced <em>The Times</em> (London) to publish them. The puzzle quickly spread 
                        to other newspapers worldwide.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="timeline-item">
                <div class="timeline-marker">2005-Present</div>
                <div class="timeline-content">
                    <h5>Worldwide Popularity</h5>
                    <p>
                        Sudoku became a global sensation, appearing in newspapers, puzzle books, mobile apps, 
                        and websites. World Sudoku Championships began in 2006. Today, millions solve Sudoku 
                        puzzles daily, with dedicated apps, tournaments, and even Sudoku variants emerging.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section mb-5">
        <h2 class="section-title">How to Play</h2>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
                <div class="rule-card">
                    <div class="rule-number">1</div>
                    <h4>Row Rule</h4>
                    <p>Each <strong>horizontal row</strong> must contain the digits 1-9 without repetition.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
                <div class="rule-card">
                    <div class="rule-number">2</div>
                    <h4>Column Rule</h4>
                    <p>Each <strong>vertical column</strong> must contain the digits 1-9 without repetition.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
                <div class="rule-card">
                    <div class="rule-number">3</div>
                    <h4>Box Rule</h4>
                    <p>Each <strong>3×3 box</strong> (also called regions or blocks) must contain the digits 1-9 without repetition.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
                <div class="rule-card">
                    <div class="rule-number">4</div>
                    <h4>Given Numbers</h4>
                    <p>Some cells are <strong>pre-filled</strong> and cannot be changed. Use logic to fill the remaining empty cells.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section mb-5">
        <h2 class="section-title">Solving Strategies</h2>
        <div class="accordion" id="strategiesAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                    <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#strategy1">
                        <strong>Beginner: Naked Singles</strong>
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="strategy1" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" data-bs-parent="#strategiesAccordion">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                        Look for cells where only one number can fit. Check what numbers are already in the same row, 
                        column, and 3×3 box. If only one number is missing, that's your answer!
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#strategy2">
                        <strong>Beginner: Hidden Singles</strong>
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="strategy2" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#strategiesAccordion">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                        Within a row, column, or box, look for a number that can only go in one cell. Even if that cell 
                        could hold multiple numbers, if a specific number has only one valid position, place it there.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#strategy3">
                        <strong>Intermediate: Naked Pairs/Triples</strong>
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="strategy3" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#strategiesAccordion">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                        When two cells in a row, column, or box can only contain the same two numbers, those numbers 
                        can be eliminated from other cells in that group. This works for triples and quadruples too!
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#strategy4">
                        <strong>Advanced: X-Wing</strong>
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="strategy4" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#strategiesAccordion">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                        If a candidate number appears in only two positions across two rows (or columns), and these 
                        positions align vertically (or horizontally), you can eliminate that candidate from the 
                        intersecting columns (or rows).
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

